<subSubSection box="[151,579,1245,1271]" pageId="36" pageNumber="59" type="multiple">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,1245,1594]" box="[151,579,1245,1271]" pageId="36" pageNumber="59">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,579,1245,1271]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="36" pageNumber="59" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,579,1245,1271]" pageId="36" pageNumber="59">Apterous viviparous female (exules)</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="59" type="key">
<key pageId="36" pageNumber="59">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,1245,1594]" pageId="36" pageNumber="59">
<keyLead pageId="36" pageNumber="59">
<keyStep pageId="36" pageNumber="59">
1. Siphunculi with 9–20 finely pointed setae. Processus terminalis 1.56–2.17 times as long as base of last antennal segment. The longest setae on 3rd antennal segment—76–95, on abdominal tergite III—81–101; the ratio of the longest setae on 3rd antennal segment and the longest setae on abdominal tergite III to the articular diameter of the 3rd antennal segment 2.90–4.00 and 3.10–4.13 respectively. Third antennal segment with 42–57, base of last antennal segment with 10–14 setae. Pheromone plates on the hind tibia are located in the distal third of the tibia closer to its outer margin.................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Pashtshenko, 1988)" authorityName="Stekolshchikov" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Pashtshenko" baseAuthorityYear="1988" box="[1034,1436,1424,1447]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Neoceruraphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudosensoriata">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1034,1235,1424,1446]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="59">N. pseudosensoriata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Pashtshenko, N. F." box="[1247,1429,1425,1447]" pageId="36" pageNumber="59" pagination="1580 - 1583" refId="ref19549" refString="Pashtshenko, N. F. (1988) New genus and species of the aphid (Homoptera, Aphididae) from the Soviet Far East. Zoologicheskii Zhurnal, 67 (10), 1580 - 1583. [In Russian]" type="journal article" year="1988">Pashtshenko, 1988</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
</keyStep>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1436,1245,1594]" pageId="36" pageNumber="59">
<keyLead pageId="36" pageNumber="59">
<keyStep pageId="36" pageNumber="59">
2. Siphunculi without setae. Processus terminalis 2.67–3.63 times as long as base of last antennal segment. The longest setae on 3rd antennal segment—38–53, on abdominal tergite III—37–45; the ratio of the longest setae on 3rd antennal segment and the longest setae on abdominal tergite III to the articular diameter of the 3rd antennal segment 1.67–2.38 and 1.53–2.00 respectively. Third antennal segment with 23–31, base of last antennal segment with 2–3 setae. Pheromone plates on the hind tibia are located in the distal half of the tibia closer to its inner margin........................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gillette, 1909)" baseAuthorityName="Gillette" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[1140,1436,1571,1594]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Neoceruraphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="59" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viburnicola">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1140,1282,1571,1593]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="59">N. viburnicola</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gillette, C. P." box="[1295,1429,1572,1594]" pageId="36" pageNumber="59" pagination="280 - 285" refId="ref18739" refString="Gillette, C. P. (1909) American snowball louse, Aphis viburnicola n. sp. Entomological News, 20, 280 - 285." type="journal article" year="1909">Gillette, 1909</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
</keyStep>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</key>
